<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,418,792]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">
This single female is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2005" authorityName="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2005" box="[613,1149,418,444]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachydromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terricoloides">
<emphasis box="[613,793,418,443]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">T. terricoloides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev" box="[801,1149,418,444]" pageId="6" pageNumber="43" refString="Shamshev, I., Grootaert, P. &amp; Stark, A. (2005) Notes on a remarkable abdominal structure in some Crossopalpus Bigot species (Diptera: Hybotidae), with new records from Southeast Asia. Studia dipterologica, 12, 331 - 336." type="journal article" year="2005">
Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 
<number box="[1088,1149,418,444]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but because the male is unknown, we did not name it. The antennae are completely yellow and the basal segments are not darkened as in 
<taxonomicName box="[182,363,496,521]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachydromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terricoloides">
<emphasis box="[182,363,496,521]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">T. terricoloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It has a black thorax instead of the yellowish-brown thorax in 
<taxonomicName box="[1121,1302,496,521]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachydromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terricoloides">
<emphasis box="[1121,1302,496,521]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">T. terricoloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There is a pair of pale dorsocentrals near the middle of the mesonotum that are longer than the other dorsocentrals. The halter has a black knob rather than a yellow knob. The legs are completely yellow including all coxae, but tip of fore tarsomere 
<number box="[361,376,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="1.0">1</number>
is ventrally brown, fore tarsomeres 
<number box="[803,817,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[875,890,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="3.0">3</number>
are clear yellow, tip of tarsomere 
<number box="[1294,1308,612,638]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="4.0">4</number>
and apical half of tarsomere 
<number box="[358,372,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="5.0">5</number>
brown. Tips of mid and hind tarsomeres 
<number box="[856,871,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="4.0">4</number>
and 
<number box="[927,942,650,676]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" value="5.0">5</number>
brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
